# Announcing Validation Settings Update 📢 
https://github.com/macrocosm-os/finetuning/tree/v3.1.0

Phase 1 of validation stability improvements, monitoring will follow so please keep bringing your feedback! 
These are the results of experiments trying to stabilize vtrust among validators, we will focus next on the validation flow ideas reported by @PawKanarek and @coffiee  👍

- Increased SYNC_BLOCK_CADENCE from 270 to 360

## Notes to validators
Please make sure to increase the number of open files limit before running the validator, then update the dependencies:
```
$ ulimit -n 64000
$ python -m pip install -e .
```

Sorry guys. We appreciate your patience. We are burning the minute oil on a major release and I have @roel [τ, α] | Macrocosmos locked in a vault under key. There is an instability here that is coming from less validators running infra. We will see if there is a patch but this architecture may need to fundamentally change.
Note this is training R&D, so not directly related to the competitions change you’re requesting.
If people in this subnet have hotfix suggestions / PRs, please be my guest and participate as members of this community.

Some ideas:
1) Make sure that winner models will always be rewarded and picked to next round
2) There is bug that happened to me and  @Biust  long time ago https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1253448873305964626/1326858713612681226. In summary, there is possibility that your weights could be assigned to someone else if he will be lucky to register UID in correct time. For example: at 10:00 you were picked to evaluation, evaluation finished at 10:10, but your UID was pretty old. At 10:05 someone else reigstered new miner and he got your old UID, before assigning weights at 10:10. Boom! new user will get your weights. I believe thats why we observed so much spam with registration in this competition. 
3) Scoring should be deterministic (in this regards competition 3B reasoning was much better than old competitions)
4) It was cool to see how best miner model was scored on public benchmarks

5) If datasets in competition constrains are small (<5GB) then competition should end quickly e.g. 2 weeks / month, because models will be degenerated by miners that are trying to overfit on small dataset

Hi @PawKanarek , we have restarted our vali and will be monitoring the vali's ranking. I think what you observe here is caused by the variance problem, different miners can get different rankings on different validators, when the seed value switches before validating the other miner one on vali but not the other.
So let's say
-vali 1:
miner 1 and 2 gets evaluated on seed A

- vali2:
miner 1 gets evaluated on seed A
then seed switches to B
miner 2 gets evaluated on seed B

In a context where variance from one batch to another on a given dataset is high, miner 1 and 2 can get different rankings on different valis on these seed switches.

The solution would be to decrease variance either by increasing the batch size, or by smoothing loss over many batches for a given miner. We'll look into what can be done

and the output 
```
(ft) ➜  ~/test git:(ft) ✗ python bug_simulation.py 
--- Test Case ---
Input Win Rates: {108: 1.0, 21: 0.2, 22: 0.1}
Input Historical Tracker Weights: {108: 0.0005, 21: 0.001, 22: 0.0}
Sample Min (models to keep): 1

Calculated Priorities: {108: 1.0, 21: 1.001, 22: 0.1}

UIDs Sorted by Priority (descending): [21, 108, 22]
Models Selected to Keep: {21}

--- Bug Explanation ---
BUG CONFIRMED: UID 108 (Win Rate: 1.0) was NOT selected.
Instead, UID 21 (Win Rate: 0.2, Historical Weight: 0.001) was selected.
This is because:
  - Priority of Actual Winner (UID 108): 1.0000 (derived from its win rate directly)
  - Priority of Poor Performer A (UID 21): 1.0010 (derived from 1 + its minimal historical weight)
The poor performer's priority is higher, causing the actual winner to be dropped when sample_min is restrictive.

Test with sample_min = 2 to see who comes second:
--- Test Case ---
Input Win Rates: {108: 1.0, 21: 0.2, 22: 0.1}
Input Historical Tracker Weights: {108: 0.0005, 21: 0.001, 22: 0.0}
Sample Min (models to keep): 2

Calculated Priorities: {108: 1.0, 21: 1.001, 22: 0.1}

UIDs Sorted by Priority (descending): [21, 108, 22]
Models Selected to Keep: {108, 21}

With sample_min = 2, both UID 21 (higher priority) and UID 108 (lower priority) are kept.

The actual winner (UID 108) is dropped, and a model that performed poorly in the current round (UID 21) is kept instead, purely due to its minimal historical weight just meeting the threshold. This is the bug in action.
```

We are not in the business of hype-based promotion.

Burning miner emissions has become the new `meta` in bittensor following the introduction of dTao. Currently, 52 active subnets are burning their emissions 😦 I made simple GUI to visualise this:  https://huggingface.co/spaces/pawkanarek/burntensor

I think that in the pre-dTao era, most subnet owners focused on cool ML ideas. For example, here on sn37, we were training small 3B LLMs on small datasets (<10 GB).

TBH, this is not very interesting from an investor perspective, because it doesn't provide real value, in fact we were overfitting this model so hard it couldn't even generate normal text outside this datasets. So the subnet's token price would drop as miners would dump their tokens, and this would cause holders to lose value and sell their tokens as well, ultimately leading to the subnet's real death. (now i would say that this subnet is in coma :D)

In dTao era, sn owners must implement new ideas that are valuable not only from ML perspective but also from an investor's perspective. Furthermore, the old scoring system, where a single miner could receive 100% of the rewards, could cause significant price instability, thus, having deprecated idea and miner scoring, owners started to burn emissions so at least alpha holders would not loose the value.

TL;DR, many subnets that were created before dTao are now burning miner emissions because their original concepts do not align with the dTao-era ecosystem.
But i have strong faith in Macrocosmos team,  cuz they are smart :D. Implementing new ideas is not just that easy, and they are focusing thier Brians on sn9 :p
and well why only miners emissions are burnt? Because that's the only  way of burning alpha on bittensor chain.
I wrote a long response on my views on burn in the SN1 channel (won't repost here), but tldr; subnets need better tools to manage emission control
You can't just pause reg and "stop" the subnet anymore - if you shut off reg, alpha flow continues, but TAO flow doesn't (so price drops off a cliff)

Without disclosing too much, we had another full architecture ready for this subnet that we chose not to ship for several reasons. @PawKanarek is right that the SN37 competition had finished it's course, and we didn't have conviction in the long term viability of the model competition network design (which is one of the reasons we built iota). Spending engineering hours on a dead architecture isn't worthwhile.

We left the competition up, but when we had a validator hack, it didn't make sense to restart the old, stagnant competition, so we started burning.

There are a lot of people contributing to some of these mechanisms behind the scenes (we are one of them), but it also links to things like root weight, sell pressure, and a multitude of other hyperparameters
tldr; adding any change to a significant hyperparameter in dTAO can introduce fluctuations through the system that can potentially be exploited, so it's not as easy as we'd all love it to be

Hey SN37 fans.

Earlier this year, we shifted SN37 to burn as we launched iota, and began a period of introspection. We pulled together an architecture for SN37 that we ultimately chose not to release. We spent a lot of time working on what a great future for SN37 was, and are pleased to announce that today, that has come to fruition.

We were approached by a great team that we met at Proof of Talk - Aurelius, who are excited to launch Bittensor's first Alignment subnet. At Macrocosmos, this is an issue near and dear to our hearts, and we felt it was a phenomenal successor to the existing fine tuning design, that previous supporters and investors in this slot will celebrate, and we hope find conviction in (as we have).

We vetted many teams, and settled on the absolute best we could find. We will  support Aurelius in driving this subnet forward by providing advice, support, and remaining significant holders in this subnet.

We are thrilled to welcome Aurelius to Bittensor, and can't wait to see what they build. @Ausτin is the man in charge! 

Macrocosmos will continue to focus on it's prime objective of creating open intelligence for all on Bittensor.

We triggered the cold key swap today, so in 5 days the team will be able to release and start bringing their subnet to market! 

We'll be pushing press releases and content in this shortly.

Aurelius doesn't do anything like that. Instead what I'm referring to is the abilty to speed-run some of the technical challenges that are necessary for our subnet to function by partnering with existing subnets, and then to also concentrate our miner outputs into a dataset that is custom built for fine-tuning of models for alignment purposes that can then be turned around and plugged into yet another subnet. For example, any subnet training models could benefit from bespoke supervised fine-tuning datasets that make the model more performant across specific alignment dimensions. This is an value-add that bittensor-made models could take advantage of, but not limited to bittensor only
